	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Photoshop isn't very suitable for pixel graphics, although if you get used to it already, it'll work.
<br />
<br />There are two ways to make NES graphics.
<br />
<br />You can make it in a specialized editor that will check all the limitations automatically, not allowing you to draw anything that couldn't be displayed on NES. Downside is that these specialized editors are usually very limited compared to normal graphics editor, i.e. it is just difficult to work with them.
<br />
<br />You can make graphics in any normal graphics editor, keeping NES limitations in mind (colors per tile, palettes, attributes), then convert it with a specialized tool. This way you will be able to do major part of work in a comfortable tool.
<br />
<br />I personally use both ways, depending from complexity of the graphics.
<br />
<br />I don't know about specialized tools for Mac, though, but you always can use Windows tools through Wine, and there was a tile editor in Java, forgot its name.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


